      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Ammonia reacts with acetyl chloride (CH<sub>3</sub>COCl) to give acetamide (CH<sub>3</sub>CONH<sub>2</sub>). Identify the bonds broken and formed in each step of the reaction, and draw curved arrows to represent the flow of electrons in each step.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaGNXIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--20b4159316739449f0a977e271021a14a06856e4/OSX_OrgChem_06_99_OChem-06-EC-023_80485-06-u074_P-AcetylCh_img.jpg\" alt=\"A 3-step reaction of acetyl chloride with ammonia. Step 1: ammonia addition to carbonyl; step 2: chlorine is eliminated; step 3: acetamide product is deprotonated by ammonia, ammonium chloride formed.\">",
